New Yorkers were rocked awake this morning as an earthquake struck the Buffalo area, A magnitude 3.8 earthquake hit at around 6.15am, with hundreds of people filing shaking reports according to the United States Geological Survey. The quake was initially reported as a more substantial 4.2 seismic event but the intensity level was later dropped. The shaking was considered "light" from the event but, he United States Earthquake tracker also said: “M 3.8 - 2 km ENE of West Seneca, New York.” The centre of the quake was in West Seneca, officials said, and happened about 3.0 km underground. Shaking was felt as far north as Niagara Falls and as far sound as south to Orchard Park, Erie County Executive Mark Poloncarz said on Twitter. "It felt like a car hit my house in Buffalo. I jumped out of bed," he said. New York Governor Kathy Hochul added that “no damage has been reported at this time”. West Seneca Police joked: “Well good morning everyone. Just your usual Buffalo morning earthquake, back to bed.” While data is preliminary, this could mean the quake was the largest earthquake felt in the Western New York area in the past 33 years. The USGS said this part of southern Ontario and western New York State has had moderately frequent earthquakes at least since the first one was reported in 1840. The largest, a magnitude 4.9 quake, caused moderate damage in 1929 near Attica, New York. And in 1990, a 3.3 magnitude quake was felt in St. Catharine’s, Ontario, Canada, but also felt in New York.